@Node "WhatIs"
                        @{b}What is Dear Diary then?@{ub}
                        @{b}------------------------@{ub}

    Dear Diary is not another personal organiser program you'll be happy to
here, it is in fact a computerised private diary in which you can write your
most intimate secrets and be sure that nobody will be else will be able to
read it.  The advantages over a normal paper diary are obvious.  Firstly
the entries are encoded so that nobody, except perhaps the government;)
can read it without a password or into another wordprocessor.  No more
embarasing photocopys around the school;)

    Anybody can use this program, be them young, old, or just plain stupid.
but if you use it a lot make sure you register it by sending Ł5-or more;)
to me to insure continued development. I'm a financially challanged college
student who survives on no more than bread and water <for added guilt>.
@endnode

@Node "Install"
                      @{b}Installing Dear Diary V3.0@{ub}
                      @{b}--------------------------@{ub}

@{b}So you want to put it on your hard drive?@{ub}

    Easy, Just run the installer program and follow the instructions.

If you don't have the installer then follow these instructions.

Copy the disk to a drawer on your hard drive but draging the disk icon to
where ever you want to install it to or if you want to use the CLI type this:

    Copy DF0: TO DH1:Dear_Diary

(where DH1:Dear_Diary can be replaced with any place on your HD.)

Before Dear_Diary can be run it must be assigned to that drawer by typing

    Assign Dear_Diary: DH1:Dear_Diary

(where DH1:Dear_Diary is where you placed it above)

you should add this line to your s:startup-sequence just before the LoadWb
command to save typing this every time you run it.

(you can edit the s:startup-sequence by typing 'Ed S:Startup-Sequence')

    Easy Ugh! - come on it's only two lines;-)
 
@endnode
 
@Node "HowTo"
                       @{b}Setting Up Dear Diary V3.0@{ub}
                       @{b}--------------------------@{ub}

      To start off you will have to tell the diary where you want your 
entries to be saved to. To do this click on the Select Drive icon. (It's on 
the bottom left corner of the diary screen.) This will bring up a requestor,
you can either click on one of the gadgets corresponding to a drive, or
if you want to be more precise you can click on the Select Drive icon and 
using the file requestor locate where you want your entries saved. If you
are happy with your selection just click on OK, if not click on Cancel.
After doing so a directry will be created where you selected it to be called
Diary_Entries. Dear Diary will save your choice to the S: directory of your
system disk and recall it when needed.

       The other icons are Quit which exits to the workbench screen.
       
       @{"About" Link ShareWare} shows information about the programer (ME!)
       
       The Workbench icon will open or shut the workbench screen. To switch
to this screen hold down the Left Amiga Key and then press 'A' and the same
is used to get back to Dear Diary. 
       Change Password is used to, errr... change the password. More than
person can use Dear Diary at a time so it is possible to have a password
for each user. 

       The Last icon of all is in the shape of a key hole. Click on this
to begin typing your entry. @{"Click here for more information" Link MkEntry}

@endnode

@Node "MkEntry"
                          @{b}Making an Entry@{ub}
                          @{b}---------------@{ub}

       Dear Diary's text editor will display the currently edited date
which can be changed by clicking on the yellow arrow icons. It works like
a video recorder (well sort of).
                   ||< back one year    |< one month < one day. 
                   >|| forward one year >| one month > one day. 

       On loading the date will be taken from the battery backup clock if 
one is present.
       The rest is simple, just type. All entries are saved when you change
the date of attempt to quit by pressing ESCape. Quit the ­program before
resetting your computer or your entries may be lost.

       The text editor is very simple and only has Word Wrap but if you
would like the code see @{"ProgramCode." Link ProgramCode}
       
 
@endnode

